+{"id":"bd-n8blq","title":"Conformance harness: build syscall-level conformance tests vs reference fs","description":"Apply /testing-conformance-harnesses skill. Build a conformance test that drives our fs through the same syscall sequences as a reference (Linux ext4 in tmpfs). Differential diff outputs per syscall (return value, errno, side effects). Cover: file lifecycle, directory ops, attribute ops, link semantics, mmap interaction, fsync semantics, mount/umount.","notes":"Extended the existing syscall-level differential harness with offset I/O coverage: Linux reference vs mounted FrankenFS now compares pread/pwrite, SEEK_END, fdatasync fallback behavior, final file bytes/size/link mode metadata, alongside existing lifecycle/dir/link/mmap/fsync steps. Fresh-eyes cleanup hardening now tolerates the Python offset-I/O skip path without unlinking a missing io.bin. Validation: targeted fuse_conformance_syscall_sequence_matches_linux_reference passed after the cleanup fix with worker FUSE mount soft-skip after reference probe; fmt and UBS touched files passed. Earlier full gates for this final slice passed before the cleanup-only hardening: workspace check, workspace clippy, parity_report_matches_feature_parity_md, full ffs-harness tests, and cargo bench -p ffs-harness. Criterion reported an ext4_group_desc_32byte microbenchmark regression, but no parser code changed in this slice. Agent Mail remained red, so no reservation/release.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"cod-fs","created_at":"2026-04-24T22:22:37.099317207Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T04:55:41.762173117Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
